Chancellor: Why I would lay hands on the princess, if you
want to know, I shall tell you. Now then... where should I
begin explaining?

Chancellor: Now Reisha, do you know? There is a secret
within the royal bloodline.
A secret, you say...?

Chancellor: Why are there so many short-lived individuals in
the Near Lake royal lineage? Why is there a difference in
the order of succession to the throne from birth?

Chancellor: The fact that many past kings began to exhibit
their talents and the stronger their brilliance, the more
madly they raged and met tragic ends.

Chancellor: The words 'my blood is thin' that slipped from
the mouth of His Highness the Crown Prince amidst the recent
succession disputes one day in frustration.

Chancellor: The illness of His Highness the Crown Prince,
the defection of His Highness the elder brother, the
uncharacteristic frenzy and death of the wise previous king.

Chancellor: The words of His Highness the elder brother made
many things click. And from that day I heard them, I became
obsessed with the royal blood.

Chancellor: The existence of a special magical power
mediated by blood. A secret magic passed down only within
certain family lines.

Chancellor: Using my position and gaining collaborators,
research progressed. The relationship between blood flowing
within humans and magic reached profound depths.
Chancellor: But what about it?

Chancellor: The only girl who possesses the royal bloodline
that I most wanted to understand was closest to me, yet her
temperament was farthest from me, isn't it laughable?

Chancellor: She won't be swayed by benefits or allow deceit.
She's steadfast in her love for the country. She must know
full well that without my connections and skills, governance
would falter.

Chancellor: It was quite a struggle to get into her good
graces.

Chancellor: She was a sullen princess and hard to handle,
but why is it, Reisha? When your name comes up, she
immediately takes interest. You are greatly trusted by her.

Chancellor: She listened intently with shining eyes when I
talked about our time at court school where I briefly
instructed you. Such an adorable thing. Unaware of what
would befall her later.

Chancellor: To capture her... perhaps that doesn't sound too
good. I invited her here to cooperate with our magical
experiments and then it became clear.

Chancellor: The treasured sword of the royal family, "Sword
of Dawn." Its radiance is said to lead the country to dawn,
a supreme treasure according to legend.

Chancellor: It is said that a king from a generation with a
particularly strong royal bloodline and awakened magical
powers could extract and materialize immense magical energy
from his own blood.

Chancellor: The blood-soaked treasured sword overwhelms
everything, and with its unparalleled power, it thunders the
path of conquest. Its form, turning battlefields into
scorched earth and mowing down enemy soldiers, is a weapon
itself. To think such a thing is considered a treasure.

Chancellor: It's laughable, isn't it? The royal treasure
thought to be lost is in my hands, yet despite that, it has
been forgotten by all, and the country is declining like
this.

Chancellor: Have you ever experienced it? The feeling of
being able to do nothing but watch as the country you
believed in weakens.

Chancellor: That's why I will revive it. I will awaken the
royal blood and with magic, make this country resound
throughout the world!!

Chancellor: I will take that first step on the path of
conquest that my lord, the previous king, could not
achieve!!

Chancellor: For my plans, your existence was an obstacle.

Chancellor: You live by the knight's code of this country,
not swayed by profit and sticking to righteousness. I knew
you would never lend an ear to my true intentions.

Chancellor: It would be troublesome if there was an uproar.
I wanted to get rid of the nuisance before the plan was
discovered, and then useful information came in.

Chancellor: If I could send you far away, that would be
good; if you died on your journey, even better. A knight
abandoning his mission and returning empty-handed is
something you would never allow yourself.

Chancellor: "You" will obey if it's "for the lord," and "our
king" will easily accept my opinion if it's "for the
knight."

Chancellor: Bonds and emotions can sometimes cloud one's
vision, you half-baked lot.

Is that all you wanted to say? Are you planning to give a
speech now?

I understand what you want to say. If you're expecting me to

If buying time is your aim, it's transparent. Don't bother
asking me to change my mind now. The sights I've witnessed
are more than enough to condemn you.
Take care not to let this sword strike fly immediately...!!

Chancellor: Hmph, so it is. This is why knights are no good.
Always too quick to fight.

Chancellor: Although, as it stands now, I am in the position
of a knight protecting the monarch. The first step on my
path of conquest. I've finally obtained it; I won't give it

I will never allow you to speak of chivalry with that

Chancellor: Unable to sense danger, the lord you should
protect is exposed to peril, and on top of that, you rush
about on a journey orchestrated to search for a non-existent

Chancellor: What else can this be called but foolishness? If
such a thing is called knighthood, then I have no need for
it.
Hah...!

Chancellor: It's been a long time since I've been away, but

the country.
Chancellor: Although strictly speaking...
Chancellor: My true talent lay in this area.

To our lord... no, not just that. For the many sins
committed against those you have harmed, your body will more
than suffice as atonement.
All your past atrocities will never be forgiven—!!
Chancellor: Don't underestimate me, you outdated knight!

Chancellor: The awakening of the royal bloodline is near! If

Chancellor: Here I go...—!!

I've come this far... am I still not enough...
